WEBVTT

00:30.562 --> 00:33.646
Church is always, it is such a delight and a privilege to get to be with you.

00:33.706 --> 00:41.255
My name is Mike, one of the teaching pastors here at The Well, and I get the honor, once again, of launching us into a new series called Monarchy.

00:41.875 --> 00:54.450
We're gonna spend now, the next year, by the way, being in a series of three of the greatest kings in the nation of Israel, Saul, David, and Solomon, kings whose lives that you are very familiar with.

00:54.790 --> 00:57.874
And yet we get the beauty of seeing this kind of

00:57.922 --> 01:06.109
in a rear view mirror that all of this is going to be in light of the King of Kings Jesus as we talk about God's rule and reign in our lives through a King.

01:06.750 --> 01:09.672
This is selfishly a series that I've had on the radar is a long time.

01:09.712 --> 01:14.516
I've been excited about maybe getting into it and maybe more excited was just the artwork that you guys got to see.

01:14.536 --> 01:20.402
If the teaching is half as good as our creative team is in putting these pictures together, I think we're in for a great series.

01:20.942 --> 01:26.026
In all honesty, I think it's just helpful at times to let you guys into the secret sauce that makes the well.

01:26.627 --> 01:27.908
We sit in teams with our

01:27.888 --> 01:34.917
Our creative team, our teaching team, and the scripture forms where we're going and what we're doing as a teaching community.

01:35.538 --> 01:46.392
And those folks that sit in the room, Casey Jackson and Rachel Just, that are part of our creative process, they design artwork and bumpers and all the things that we get to enjoy, they are all driven by the text together.

01:46.473 --> 01:50.638
So super impressed with them, grateful for incredible people that I get to work with.

01:50.658 --> 01:56.626
But as you see these things, I just want you to know they're very much intentional and connected to what we're doing in a series.

01:56.674 --> 02:04.953
We are, as I mentioned, going to be here for now the next year, and we're going to study this beautiful section of God's Word in our Old Testament in light of what we see, obviously, in Christ.

02:05.334 --> 02:06.436
And we can jump in right now.

02:06.456 --> 02:12.450
I mean, we can turn in our Bibles to 1 Samuel 8, and we can start talking about the very first king in the nation of Israel who was Saul.

02:12.951 --> 02:16.178
But I think if we did that, we'd be missing something.

02:16.610 --> 02:20.178
There is a power to the back story, to understanding.

02:20.239 --> 02:21.401
How did we get here?

02:21.662 --> 02:22.905
Why do we have kings?

02:23.125 --> 02:27.195
Why is God allowing this season and the rule and reign of Israel?

02:27.215 --> 02:28.197
What is he doing?

02:28.779 --> 02:33.650
That back story is so helpful to kind of setting the stage and helping us build some understanding.

02:34.082 --> 02:40.292
I was reminded by the way, the importance and the power of back story here on a recent trip to Nashville with some of my high school buddies.

02:40.332 --> 02:42.997
Some of my buddies and I, we still regularly get together and hang out.

02:43.017 --> 02:46.622
And this year we went to Nashville and we went to a place called the Bluebird Cafe.

02:47.063 --> 02:48.085
Some of you may have heard of it.

02:48.145 --> 02:49.207
Really, really cool place.

02:49.307 --> 02:53.714
It is the most random, like out of the way, like,

02:54.146 --> 02:57.470
Humble little joint, it seats 90 different people like in the room.

02:57.511 --> 02:58.993
It's really, really quaint and small.

02:59.593 --> 03:01.175
It's literally in a strip mall, right?

03:01.216 --> 03:05.461
So far removed from Nashville, downtown, music scene.

03:05.521 --> 03:07.784
It literally is next to a dry cleaners and a hair salon.

03:08.666 --> 03:09.587
Crazy little place.

03:09.727 --> 03:11.029
And they're world famous.

03:11.509 --> 03:16.857
If you're anybody who's anybody in country music, you have a bluebird story to tell.

03:17.437 --> 03:23.826
On your rise to fame at some point in your career, you played there in front of just 90 people.

03:24.002 --> 03:32.178
uh... but with the bluebird cafe became famous for wasn't so much their artist nights but their songwriters nights and that's the night i got to attend

03:32.514 --> 03:46.691
and these individuals who have written the songs to all the mega hits that you know if you adore country music, they're the ones that write the songs and they sit literally in the round and you sit around them as they're sharing stories behind how this song came about.

03:47.072 --> 03:54.361
Songs, by the way, as a kid who grew up in Texas and country music that I loved, I knew everyone in the room could sing these songs by heart.

03:54.381 --> 03:58.706
We already knew and loved and adored them, but understanding the backstory

03:59.074 --> 04:01.277
Understanding how this song came to be.

04:01.337 --> 04:10.970
The things that were happening in this song writer's life that entered into this song now that George Strait or Garth Brooks or Taylor Swift is singing were just so much more powerful.

04:11.410 --> 04:14.615
And it reminded me as we dive into the series, there's an importance to that.

04:15.256 --> 04:21.183
Understanding the backstory of what God's doing and why he's doing it enhances our understanding of all of this.

04:21.684 --> 04:24.027
And I wanna make sure in our time together we don't miss that.

04:24.448 --> 04:26.130
So what I would like to do is back up

04:26.658 --> 04:35.411
hundreds of years before these kings hit the stage and talk about the why and the how and the what that formed the series that we're going to look at.

04:35.932 --> 04:40.098
So as I thought about maybe the best place to start, I thought probably no better place to start than the beginning.

04:40.298 --> 04:45.586
So turn in your Bible to Genesis 1 verse 1 and we're going to begin our time together there today.

04:45.698 --> 04:52.566
While most of the series, by the way, we'll plant ourselves in a text and we will work through kind of as we normally do a section of scripture.

04:52.646 --> 04:55.530
This is going to be much more of a rock skipping across a pond.

04:56.010 --> 05:01.697
So if you want to get your fingers like moving and skip verses with me, you are more than welcome to do that.

05:02.277 --> 05:09.386
If you just want to kind of settle in and grab a pen and make reference to the verses that we're going to go through, that may make your hand a little less tired today.

05:09.906 --> 05:13.010
But we are going to kind of walk through the grand narrative of this story.

05:13.058 --> 05:21.288
So in Genesis chapter 1 and this idea of a king, listen to how the very Bible begins in describing the person and character and nature of God.

05:21.969 --> 05:25.954
It says, in the beginning, God created the heavens and the earth.

05:26.454 --> 05:35.826
As we open up our Bible for the very first time, we are introduced to a God who rules and reigns in sovereignty over all of creation.

05:36.290 --> 05:40.535
He has a unique ability to create the universe and all that is in it.

05:40.876 --> 05:51.409
In fact, the very word here used in Genesis 1-4, God, has the idea of royalty, of majesty, a pre-existent God over all things.

05:51.830 --> 05:58.238
So he comes on the scene for us in the person as really a king in some way, shape, or form.

05:58.638 --> 06:01.362
In fact, Israel understood him that way.

06:01.802 --> 06:04.786
Listen to the prophet Jeremiah who later describes God this way.

06:05.250 --> 06:07.913
Who would not fear you, O king of the nations?

06:08.493 --> 06:09.894
Indeed, it is your do.

06:09.954 --> 06:18.102
For among all the wise men of the nations and all their kingdoms, there is none like you, Jeremiah, chapter 10, verse seven.

06:18.663 --> 06:24.668
The psalmist in Psalm 145 verse one says, I will extol you, my God, O king.

06:24.708 --> 06:27.371
And I will bless your name forever and ever.

06:28.212 --> 06:35.058
Zachariah chapter 14 verse nine says, and the Lord will be king over all the earth.

06:35.426 --> 06:40.933
In that day, the Lord will be the only one in his name, the only one.

06:41.434 --> 06:49.805
And finally in Psalm 149 verse 2 says, let Israel be glad in his maker, let the sons of Zion rejoice in their king.

06:50.466 --> 06:59.218
So it is a very normative and natural understanding for the nature, the nation of Israel to understand God as a king who ruled over them in complete sovereignty.

06:59.650 --> 07:09.201
And from the pages of Genesis 1-1, as God now moves forward and the creation narrative fills the earth and begins to now watch this thing that he created get into motion.

07:09.621 --> 07:10.802
God does something interesting.

07:11.283 --> 07:15.848
He draws now a nation unto himself, and he does it in the most unlikely of ways.

07:16.789 --> 07:24.798
The land of Canaan, the nation of Israel as we know it today had a number of people that were living in the land, and God doesn't call any of those nations to himself.

07:25.118 --> 07:28.402
In fact, he doesn't call a nation to himself at all.

07:28.546 --> 07:32.411
Turn to Genesis chapter 12 verses one through three.

07:33.112 --> 07:36.737
Let's look at what is often called the Abrahamic covenant in our Bible.

07:37.739 --> 07:43.226
Let's watch now how God is going to draw an entire nation of people to himself.

07:43.827 --> 07:47.492
Genesis 12 verses one through three, read those with me.

07:48.474 --> 07:57.266
This is now the Lord said to Abram who we know is Abraham, go forth from your country, from your relatives and from your father's house

07:57.442 --> 07:59.506
to the land that I will show you.

08:00.047 --> 08:02.190
And I will make you a great nation.

08:02.691 --> 08:03.493
I will bless you.

08:04.114 --> 08:05.696
I will make your name great.

08:06.217 --> 08:08.221
And so you shall be a blessing.

08:08.642 --> 08:11.987
And I will bless those who bless you and the one who curses you.

08:12.148 --> 08:12.849
I will curse.

08:13.230 --> 08:18.098
And in you, all of the families of the earth will be blessed.

08:18.434 --> 08:27.887
There's three aspects that are commonly drawn out of those verses, three promises, one way promises to Abraham of land that God says, I'm gonna bring you into a good land.

08:27.907 --> 08:28.909
You're not even from here.

08:29.610 --> 08:34.637
You're from a distant land, 900 miles, I'm gonna ask you to travel to come into this place.

08:34.757 --> 08:38.743
You and your bride, Sarai or Sarah, I'm promising a land.

08:39.123 --> 08:43.810
I'm also promising that from you will become a seed or descendants that come after you.

08:44.310 --> 08:46.834
So God calls barren Sarah

08:47.554 --> 08:53.620
and a man who's never had a child with his wife, and he's gonna begin a nation with the two of them.

08:53.680 --> 08:59.566
And he also says, one day from you, all the nations of the world will be blessed.

08:59.986 --> 09:12.919
Now in the long term for us, looking backwards at this story, we know the way that Abraham and his descendants ultimately blessed the entire world was that Messiah, Jesus Christ, comes from the line of Abraham.

09:13.419 --> 09:16.082
But the more immediate way

09:16.546 --> 09:21.892
that God is gonna use Israel to be a blessing as he promised was to make them distinct.

09:22.613 --> 09:25.316
He's gonna set this nation apart on earth.

09:25.916 --> 09:31.463
No other nation on planet earth will have a relationship with God quite like Israel.

09:31.843 --> 09:34.066
And it's not by the way that God lacked options.

09:34.566 --> 09:40.513
He had plenty of people that he could have chosen within the land or even outside the land, but he chose them.

09:40.553 --> 09:45.298
Deuteronomy chapter seven verse six reminds us of that fact.

09:45.858 --> 09:49.463
He says, for you are a holy people to the Lord your God.

09:49.903 --> 09:58.434
The Lord your God has chosen you to be a people for his own possession out of all the peoples who are on the face of the earth.

09:59.075 --> 10:05.603
In fact, later on in Deuteronomy chapter 32 verse 15, God will call Israel his little Jesher rune.

10:06.004 --> 10:07.085
It means upright one.

10:07.566 --> 10:11.090
It's like a pet name that a husband would have for his wife.

10:11.266 --> 10:12.688
It's this term of endearment.

10:12.708 --> 10:16.292
He says, I look at all the other nations on the earth, none are like you.

10:16.332 --> 10:19.696
You are my precious little upright possession.

10:19.736 --> 10:28.206
And it's really a picture of Israel at her best when she was walking with God what she was meant to be upright amongst the people.

10:28.967 --> 10:34.514
Now, lest we think that Abraham was brilliant or exceedingly godly,

10:34.658 --> 10:46.578
where there was any other moral excellence in him and that is what provoked God to choose him saying, oh yeah, this guy's just like the bright shining star amongst the people's Abraham was a hot mess.

10:46.882 --> 10:49.105
He's got a habitual problem with lying.

10:49.385 --> 11:04.586
He constantly is struggling with his flesh at times, saving his own backside, putting his wife in very difficult and challenging and compromising situations, because he cared more about his own reputation and saving his own skin than even his bride.

11:05.107 --> 11:10.394
And by the way, none of that was the least bit of a surprise to God when he called Abraham.

11:10.914 --> 11:16.562
It says in Deuteronomy chapter seven, verses seven and eight, the Lord did not set his love on you.

11:16.962 --> 11:29.858
nor choose you because you were more in number than any of the peoples for you were the fewest of all peoples, but because the Lord loved you and kept the oath which he swore to your forefathers.

11:30.438 --> 11:35.965
God says, Abraham, I loved you and all the people that will come from you and I gave you an oath.

11:36.426 --> 11:41.231
I have made a covenant with you and that is the reason that I chose you out of love.

11:41.351 --> 11:43.474
I've called you into this unique position.

11:43.714 --> 11:51.768
Knowing all of that, he says, Israel, I want you to be distinct because I'm going to use you to bless the world around you.

11:52.649 --> 11:53.230
And here's how.

11:54.071 --> 11:57.678
Turn real quick to Exodus chapter 19 as the story now continues.

11:58.178 --> 12:04.028
From the calling of Abraham and Genesis chapter 12 to the giving of the law underneath Moses.

12:04.529 --> 12:09.778
He gives what are often times called the 10 commandments or the mosaic law that we were very familiar with.

12:10.018 --> 12:15.564
But before God gives this nation the law, he walks them through why I'm giving you the law.

12:16.125 --> 12:21.070
Exodus chapter 19, verses five and six.

12:21.090 --> 12:31.161
He says to Israel there, now then, if you will indeed obey my voice and keep my commandment, then you shall be my own possession amongst all the people.

12:31.722 --> 12:39.250
For all the earth is mine and you shall be, to me, a kingdom of priests and a holy nation.

12:39.682 --> 12:45.377
The role of the priests within Israel was to represent the people to God, to be the go between the mediator.

12:45.878 --> 12:50.791
In God's Israel, I want you to take that picture and that is who I am making you to be as a nation.

12:51.292 --> 12:54.380
Your job is to represent me to them.

12:54.420 --> 12:56.626
You're going to introduce these

12:56.706 --> 13:05.194
peoples that live in the land, these Canaanites, you're gonna introduce them to a very different God who is holy and wonderful and sovereign in King.

13:05.615 --> 13:11.400
You will be a priesthood of believers, so to speak, to me, a kingdom of priests is how the language is used here.

13:11.860 --> 13:17.686
And he does that through the giving of the Mosaic Law, the most famous of which are obviously the 10 commandments that we're very familiar with.

13:18.026 --> 13:22.511
Do not murder, do not steal, do not covet things that we obviously still are about today.

13:22.571 --> 13:26.034
And these things that God gives them are far more

13:26.434 --> 13:28.536
and some random list of rules.

13:28.596 --> 13:34.181
In fact, there's 613 commandments that are given to Israel here.

13:34.682 --> 13:37.144
Laws that we kind of govern their daily lives.

13:37.585 --> 13:44.891
Some of them, like the 10 commandments, are obvious to us, and we still practice those today and say, yeah, those moral laws are good and right.

13:45.312 --> 13:50.257
And yet God gives these other ones that just seem downright strange to us sometimes.

13:50.797 --> 13:53.480
Leviticus chapter 19 verse 27, one of the laws.

13:54.060 --> 13:56.082
God says, do not cut the hair

13:56.226 --> 14:00.311
at the sides of your head or trim off the edges of your beard.

14:02.013 --> 14:11.543
Verse 28 of Leviticus 19, you shall not make any cuts in your body for the dead, nor make any tattoo marks on yourselves.

14:12.224 --> 14:24.498
Leviticus chapter 19 verse 19, you are to keep my statutes, you shall not breed together two kinds of cattle, you shall not sow your field with two kinds of seed, nor wear a garment

14:24.610 --> 14:28.339
upon you with two kinds of material mixed together.

14:28.740 --> 14:29.481
What's that about?

14:30.364 --> 14:32.288
I shaved this morning before I came here.

14:32.769 --> 14:33.711
I've got a tattoo.

14:33.731 --> 14:35.055
I'm not showing you.

14:36.959 --> 14:40.648
And I see some of you all out there wearing your cotton poly blends.

14:41.710 --> 14:43.314
Sinners, all of you.

14:43.810 --> 14:45.012
Like, is that with that?

14:45.052 --> 14:46.354
Like, these are weird laws to us.

14:46.454 --> 14:47.375
Why were they there?

14:47.796 --> 14:51.561
They feel so different than do not murder, do not commit adultery, right?

14:51.841 --> 14:54.946
Those laws morally governed the day, but there was a whole nother section of laws.

14:55.366 --> 15:01.135
And God gave them laws during that day that were meant to keep them separate and distinct from the people around them.

15:01.695 --> 15:07.484
He says, shaving of beards, wearing mixed fabrics, tattoo marks, those were pagan.

15:07.924 --> 15:10.308
Those were things that pagans did during that day.

15:10.368 --> 15:12.050
And I want you to look different than them.

15:12.322 --> 15:13.885
I want you to be distinct.

15:14.285 --> 15:24.582
I want you to be separate from them in every way, how you think, how you act, how you look, so that when someone sees you, they go, ah, that's different.

15:24.602 --> 15:26.164
I don't see that every day.

15:26.525 --> 15:32.755
This group of people behaves differently, acts differently, believes differently than their pagan neighbors.

15:33.236 --> 15:39.666
So part of this was the idea that God wants them to live distinct lives from the people around them.

15:40.514 --> 15:53.812
And by the way, this was a constant struggle for Israel to be morally different, to love their neighbors, to constantly represent God, to not blend their beliefs and behaviors with the world around them.

15:54.293 --> 15:55.435
It was a constant struggle.

15:56.156 --> 16:09.394
And one of the other ways that Israel was called to be tangibly, visibly different, was that when he called Israel, when God took that nation to himself, he did not install a king over them.

16:09.922 --> 16:12.527
As you think about that idea today, it's very natural for us, right?

16:12.547 --> 16:13.369
We live in the United States.

16:13.409 --> 16:14.130
We have a president.

16:14.150 --> 16:17.877
We have a singular male, not male, sorry, or female.

16:17.897 --> 16:18.558
It could be either, right?

16:18.719 --> 16:19.480
Sorry.

16:19.500 --> 16:24.409
It could be in our case a male that rules over our land with some degree of autonomy, right?

16:24.449 --> 16:28.257
If it's Great Britain, you've got a prime minister, even in other nations around them, they have kings.

16:28.457 --> 16:31.122
We understand that idea that there's

16:31.330 --> 16:37.899
A very natural idea to have an individual who rules over you with some degree of power, right?

16:37.939 --> 16:39.721
And in Israel's day, it was no different.

16:39.781 --> 16:49.214
It was very normal, very natural for them to think there should be someone who leads us, who rules over us that is physically and yet not Israel.

16:49.635 --> 16:53.220
They are intentionally by God called to be the oddball.

16:53.780 --> 16:54.962
The question is why?

16:55.042 --> 17:01.352
Why did God not put a physical king over them when he drew Abraham and the nation to himself?

17:01.973 --> 17:03.356
And he answers that very clearly.

17:03.416 --> 17:05.900
He says, because I am your king.

17:05.960 --> 17:08.564
You have already a king.

17:08.604 --> 17:13.913
You see, the idea of theocracy was God's ideal for the nation of Israel.

17:14.394 --> 17:18.641
He was already ruling and reigning in their life.

17:19.342 --> 17:21.586
Isaiah chapter 33, verse 22.

17:21.730 --> 17:27.716
says, for the Lord is our judge, the Lord is our law giver, the Lord is our king.

17:28.216 --> 17:30.439
This was not mere liturgical language for them.

17:30.479 --> 17:33.241
This was Israel's political ideology.

17:33.622 --> 17:38.066
From the very get-go, they were called to be different and intentionally so.

17:38.606 --> 17:42.971
So God did not want them to be like all the other nations around them.

17:43.251 --> 17:50.418
They need to be distinct in their beliefs, especially with their morality, and then here as well with those who ruled over them.

17:50.946 --> 17:53.712
and yet Israel struggled with that as well.

17:54.253 --> 18:04.074
We will see the strong desire of the people to not be unique, to conform and desire a physical king to rule over them.

18:04.936 --> 18:05.617
Why is that?

18:06.199 --> 18:11.570
As you think about what Israel sees on the daily, after God allows Abraham and his

18:11.746 --> 18:14.610
His family to flourish within the land of Israel underneath Joseph.

18:14.630 --> 18:15.351
There's a famine.

18:15.711 --> 18:17.393
The whole nation ends up in Egypt.

18:17.514 --> 18:24.042
They're there for 430 years underneath the rule and reign of tyrannical kings by the name of Pharaohs.

18:24.162 --> 18:26.565
They're essentially just kings over that nation.

18:26.906 --> 18:34.195
Now some were good, in fact, even kind to Israel, but the vast majority of them were horrible kings that enslaved the people of God.

18:34.596 --> 18:39.442
But that is what they saw and that is what they got used to for 430 years.

18:39.714 --> 18:51.871
And then God, as their sovereign king, frees them from Pharaoh's oppression, brings them into the desert where they take a 40-year journey in the desert, getting Israel or getting Egypt out of Israel, so to speak.

18:52.132 --> 18:53.213
That's the book of Numbers.

18:53.594 --> 18:56.758
And then God leads them in Joshua into the promised land.

18:57.139 --> 19:02.226
And as they get into this land that God had promised Abraham, kind of for the very first time again,

19:02.466 --> 19:08.757
He says, look, you're going to see a nation around you, nations around you, in fact, that all have kings.

19:08.777 --> 19:09.878
And that's what they saw there.

19:10.279 --> 19:19.555
They saw big, strong, impressive kings over these nations who ruled and reign and went out to battle for these nations.

19:19.955 --> 19:24.202
And they found it hard to be different, hard to be set apart.

19:24.383 --> 19:28.690
They were salmon literally swimming upstream in the cultural current.

19:29.314 --> 19:34.082
So it's no surprise that this idea of a king was quite natural for them.

19:34.602 --> 19:39.250
The gravitational pull towards a king would be incredibly strong.

19:39.791 --> 19:45.700
And they had a tendency to settle for less than God's best in their life.

19:46.581 --> 19:49.466
Israel had a unique position on the world stage.

19:49.486 --> 19:51.930
They weren't significant, but they were very strategic.

19:51.950 --> 19:53.452
They were like the belly button of the world.

19:53.773 --> 19:56.978
If you wanted to get anywhere, you had to go through Israel.

19:57.090 --> 19:59.753
And you would be rubbing shoulders with this people of God.

20:00.474 --> 20:04.958
They weren't a mighty people per se, but that's how God put them into the land to be an influence.

20:05.339 --> 20:09.844
And instead of influencing others, they got influence on their journey.

20:10.664 --> 20:23.378
And as we move from the book of Joshua and the conquering of the land to the very next book in our Bible, the book of Judges, they are moving towards this fiercely, in this very morally dark day in Israel.

20:23.682 --> 20:29.390
The book of Judges arises where God allows judges to rule and reign over the people of God.

20:29.450 --> 20:35.378
Now as you think about judge, don't think courtroom and black robe, think mafia thug, think Al Capone.

20:36.039 --> 20:43.990
None of these figures were necessarily good or godly, but they were the best at the time that maybe God had.

20:44.611 --> 20:52.242
Some of them we know well, men like Gideon, women like Deborah, Samson being probably one of the most famous, and some are okay.

20:52.450 --> 20:56.115
But the vast majority of those judges were absolute moral train wrecks.

20:56.175 --> 21:04.045
In fact, the story of the Book of Judges is them kind of doing laps around the toilet bowl until they're gonna get flushed out the end, essentially.

21:04.105 --> 21:05.247
It is a dark day.

21:05.587 --> 21:13.638
And with every new judge that comes on the scene, the morality, the perspective of the people that they continues to get darker.

21:14.058 --> 21:20.146
And the story of judges is that downward spiral to them ultimately wanting a king to rule over them.

21:20.642 --> 21:29.514
In fact, we're told it is so dark morally, merrily, religiously, in all these different areas that the very theme verse of the book of Judges brings that out.

21:30.094 --> 21:33.499
It says, in those days, there was no king over Israel.

21:33.959 --> 21:37.604
And everyone did what was right in his own eyes.

21:38.605 --> 21:43.992
Part of that season was certainly a moral, just hands off the wheel for the people.

21:44.072 --> 21:48.338
They did whatever they felt was right based on the nations around them.

21:48.802 --> 21:57.071
But the other way that they chose to do what was right in their own eyes was not to live distinct specifically in their longing for a king.

21:58.112 --> 22:02.317
One of the judges that God raises up, a guy by the name of Gideon, wins a battle for them.

22:02.897 --> 22:07.242
And they are impressed as they are now freed from the Midianite oppression that they had been under now for years.

22:07.582 --> 22:18.354
And if the conclusion of this battle, the people turned to Gideon in Judges 8, and they asked him this, the men of Israel said to Gideon in Judges 8 verse 22,

22:18.626 --> 22:29.784
rule over us, both you and your son, also your son's son, for you have delivered us from the hand of Midian.

22:30.285 --> 22:33.491
Gideon, we want you to move from judge to king.

22:33.531 --> 22:38.519
And by the way, not just you, but your son and your son's sons.

22:39.000 --> 22:45.330
We're offering you Gideon a dynasty to rule over God's people.

22:45.794 --> 22:56.144
Now Gideon understood God's heart in that and wisely says, no, I will not rule over you, nor shall my son rule over you, the Lord shall rule over you.

22:56.804 --> 23:06.313
But this idea of them wanting now a king in a sense is gonna be an uphill battle moving into the book of First Samuel, the next book in our Bible after the book of Ruth of course.

23:06.674 --> 23:15.282
The die in a lot of ways is cast and they're yearning, they're longing for a physical king, they can stand no longer

23:15.746 --> 23:24.816
And as we move into first Samuel, the last and final judge, Samuel the prophet, they come to him and say, Samuel, we want a king.

23:25.116 --> 23:26.738
Give us a king.

23:27.279 --> 23:29.241
And the story is absolutely heartbreaking.

23:29.782 --> 23:36.749
In first Samuel eight, verse five, the nation says to Samuel, behold, you have grown old.

23:37.430 --> 23:40.153
Your sons do not walk in your ways.

23:40.814 --> 23:44.498
Now, appoint a king for us to judge us

23:44.802 --> 23:47.184
like the other nations.

23:48.165 --> 23:52.830
We want to be just like everyone else around us.

23:53.450 --> 23:57.514
So they come to Samuel here and they say, we want a king.

23:57.815 --> 24:01.418
They rejected the very thing that made them unique.

24:02.019 --> 24:13.650
And God says to Samuel in this moment, one of the oddest things that you'll see in your Bible, 1 Samuel 8, verse 7, God says to Samuel, listen to the voice of the people.

24:14.370 --> 24:25.804
In regard to all that they have said to you, let them have a king, for they have not rejected you, but they have rejected me from being king over them.

24:26.485 --> 24:32.092
Samuel, those people are so bent on having a king, let them have a king.

24:32.132 --> 24:35.336
Listen to their voice and allow them to do that.

24:35.576 --> 24:43.666
God says, they haven't rejected you as prophet or judge, they have rejected me as the sovereign king that rules and reigns in their life.

24:44.130 --> 24:46.974
So, these people pick a king.

24:47.755 --> 24:56.385
They think through all the characteristics that they wanna see in a king, and God allows them to choose their first king, a king by the name of Saul.

24:56.746 --> 25:02.333
In the first Samuel chapter 12, Samuel presents to them the king that they have chosen.

25:02.994 --> 25:05.237
Verse Samuel chapter 12, verse 13.

25:05.917 --> 25:12.786
It says, now therefore, here is the king whom you have chosen, whom you have asked for.

25:13.090 --> 25:16.213
and behold, the Lord has set a king over you.

25:16.574 --> 25:19.437
They got exactly what they asked for.

25:20.118 --> 25:25.564
The first king of Israel, his name again, is Saul, whose name literally means asked for.

25:27.105 --> 25:29.348
Saul, in a lot of ways, was Fabio.

25:29.848 --> 25:33.012
He is the guy that you put on the cover of all your romance novels.

25:33.072 --> 25:36.656
Ladies, when he walked into a room, you swooned, I assure you.

25:37.237 --> 25:42.162
He was the Webster's dictionary picture of what you thought a king should be.

25:42.370 --> 25:43.992
big, strong, tough guy.

25:44.393 --> 25:46.576
He was tall and bronze and handsome.

25:47.056 --> 25:50.821
He stood as we're told head and shoulders above all the other people around them.

25:51.522 --> 25:53.585
He comes from a tribe by the name of Benjamin.

25:53.785 --> 26:00.214
We're told in the book of Judges that people from his family could sling a stone out of hair and not miss.

26:00.775 --> 26:08.385
So if you wanted a king who would go out for you as a warrior and lead your people into battle, this is the king that you chose.

26:08.525 --> 26:09.266
He was

26:09.474 --> 26:13.478
perfect in every way in the mind of the people.

26:14.259 --> 26:17.743
And he reigns, by the way, for 40 years in Israel.

26:17.863 --> 26:22.508
And he begins the process of what is called the United Monarchy in Israel.

26:22.888 --> 26:30.576
Three kings who rule over a united Israel saw, then David, and then his son Solomon.

26:30.917 --> 26:35.922
Each man reigns 40 years, and each man has a very different story to tell.

26:36.194 --> 26:44.545
from Saul who literally was exactly what the people asked for, and yet Israel does not flourish underneath his rule and reign.

26:44.926 --> 26:50.273
And what we find out is though he is the perfect picture of a king on the outside.

26:50.934 --> 26:53.818
On the inside, his heart is not for the Lord.

26:54.379 --> 26:59.846
He is selfish, self-centered, and does not love God in a compelling way.

27:00.847 --> 27:03.511
And God says, okay, how'd that go for you, Israel?

27:04.232 --> 27:05.714
I let you pick your first king.

27:06.178 --> 27:08.141
40 years later, are you better off?

27:08.642 --> 27:11.186
I gave you exactly what you asked for.

27:12.087 --> 27:13.870
And he says, how about this second time?

27:14.591 --> 27:17.395
How about instead of you picking, how about I pick?

27:18.077 --> 27:31.858
How about I pick somebody based on what I see as important as a king, a guy who's ruddy, freckled face, pale, by no means impressive in stature, ladies, when he walked into a room, you didn't even notice him.

27:32.130 --> 27:35.154
In fact, he's least in his family, the last amongst his brothers.

27:35.594 --> 27:40.440
He's not from a significant tribe in Israel, so to speak, in terms of warriors like Saul was.

27:40.800 --> 27:44.244
And yet what God says is, stop looking at the outside.

27:44.745 --> 27:48.590
God does not look at the external, he looks at the heart at the internal.

27:49.070 --> 27:54.336
In this man, David, he's going to be Israel's shepherd king.

27:54.857 --> 27:56.819
And God uses him in powerful ways.

27:57.160 --> 27:59.122
Now, he is far from perfect.

27:59.458 --> 28:04.945
We'll see his journey in how he falters so frequently in his own leadership.

28:05.286 --> 28:11.794
But every other king that comes after him in the nation of Israel will be measured by David.

28:12.475 --> 28:19.925
It will be said of him either he did right like his father David did or he did not walk with the Lord as his father David had done.

28:20.426 --> 28:24.130
So as Israel's shepherd king, we'll see 40 years of his reign as well.

28:24.171 --> 28:26.834
And then finally with Solomon, David's son.

28:27.106 --> 28:28.367
This guy was regal.

28:28.788 --> 28:29.789
He was rich.

28:30.470 --> 28:33.934
The kingdom flourished for a season underneath his leadership.

28:34.354 --> 28:38.279
Solomon had more land, more influence than any other king before him.

28:38.919 --> 28:43.264
He built a house for God called the temple, took him 20 years to build.

28:43.625 --> 28:45.967
It was ostentatious beyond belief.

28:46.348 --> 28:48.170
I mean, bling to the nines.

28:48.851 --> 28:53.216
And yet what we find out is that Solomon leads with a divided heart.

28:53.836 --> 28:55.218
Partly he loves God.

28:55.522 --> 29:00.088
And partly he loves a lot of other things, and we'll see that story as we journey through.

29:00.128 --> 29:06.095
And what happens is during his reign, Israel literally collapses.

29:07.257 --> 29:17.810
And instead of having one king that ruled over one Israel, now we have a divided nation, a north and a south, an Israel and a Judah, and a different king rules

29:17.954 --> 29:21.020
over each of them, 39 kings.

29:21.040 --> 29:27.133
And by the way, most of us have no idea who they are because by and large, it's a dumpster fire of a season in Israel.

29:27.755 --> 29:31.001
19 kings in Israel in the north, not one of them was godly.

29:31.462 --> 29:32.825
All were evil kings.

29:32.905 --> 29:38.898
In the south, there's a few blips on the radar of godly kings, guys like Jehoshaphat or Asa or

29:38.978 --> 29:48.550
Josiah that maybe you've heard of, they are good in godly kings, but by and large, Israel is worse off because of the season underneath their leadership.

29:48.570 --> 30:06.112
They are deceitful, prideful, self-centered, often practicing witchcraft and even child sacrifice, worshiping the gods of the land and the people become during their rule and reign, indistinguishable from the people around them once again.

30:06.132 --> 30:07.954
They have completely blended in.

30:08.162 --> 30:11.808
with their beliefs and their practices to the pagan nations around them.

30:11.868 --> 30:14.152
So much so that God says, I'm done.

30:15.234 --> 30:18.620
All of you are getting evicted from my good land.

30:19.061 --> 30:31.341
He allows two pagan nations to come in, Assyria and Babylon, that conquer Israel, deport them, destroy the temple that Solomon took so much time building, and the reign of kings in Israel is done.

30:31.361 --> 30:34.066
This whole season of monarchy,

30:34.466 --> 30:35.648
ends in failure.

30:35.668 --> 30:48.126
42 kings who reign over them in Israel is by and large worse off than when she started because God gave them what they asked for, what they wanted.

30:49.068 --> 30:50.270
Now why would God do that?

30:51.311 --> 30:56.038
Why would God allow this season to happen in their lives?

30:56.579 --> 31:03.890
And what's even harder to reconcile is that God actually told his people long before you had a king

31:04.258 --> 31:05.680
that you would have a king.

31:05.700 --> 31:12.792
In the very second to last chapter, the book of Genesis, in chapter 49, verse 10, listen to what God prophesies.

31:13.533 --> 31:26.533
He says, the scepter, the ruling staff of a king, will not depart from Judah, nor the ruler's staff from between his feet, until he to whom it belongs shall come.

31:27.314 --> 31:30.039
And the obedience of the nations shall be his.

31:30.700 --> 31:32.082
God says from Judah,

31:32.994 --> 31:37.320
One of the tribes in Israel, from you will come a king.

31:37.360 --> 31:46.773
And we'll know that we have that rightful king because underneath his rule and reign, all of the nations will come underneath his obedience.

31:47.213 --> 31:54.684
So from the line of Judah, we'll come this king and God actually further clarifies this in 2 Samuel seven while David is ruling.

31:55.144 --> 32:02.354
He says, David, when your days are complete and you lie down with your fathers, I will raise up your descendants after you.

32:02.530 --> 32:03.852
who will come forth from you.

32:04.433 --> 32:05.995
I will establish his kingdom.

32:06.516 --> 32:09.019
He shall build a house for my name.

32:09.760 --> 32:12.864
And I will establish his kingdom forever.

32:13.625 --> 32:14.667
I will be a father to him.

32:14.727 --> 32:15.708
He will be a son to me.

32:15.728 --> 32:20.174
When he can, it's an iniquity, I will correct him with the rod of men in the strokes of the sons of men.

32:20.635 --> 32:28.626
But my loving kindness shall not depart from him as I took it away from Saul, whom I removed before you, your house,

32:28.994 --> 32:36.464
Your kingdom shall endure before me forever, and your throne shall be established forever."

32:37.105 --> 32:46.237
Now Solomon obviously is a picture of some of these promises from the God, but his house, his reign, his throne did not last forever.

32:46.698 --> 32:54.488
But God says, from you David, from your line, from Judah, will come a king who will reign forever.

32:55.569 --> 32:58.994
Not a temporary king, but a king who will rule for all eternity.

32:59.266 --> 33:03.610
So that desire for Israel to have a king is not bad or evil.

33:03.650 --> 33:11.117
In fact, it's from the Lord, but they misunderstand who that king was and what he came to do.

33:11.197 --> 33:21.967
And part of God's allowance of these kings was to show them their need for a different type of king who rules over a different type of kingdom.

33:23.168 --> 33:29.074
One day God says, I will bring you this king and he's gonna look so radically different.

33:29.442 --> 33:36.850
from any other king that you have ever seen, that most of you, especially the religious leaders of the day, you're gonna completely miss him.

33:37.470 --> 33:47.340
You won't even recognize him as king, because when he comes, we'll need to see with different types of eyes, because this king will say, my kingdom is not of this world.

33:48.221 --> 33:57.010
He'll say, I'm not what you expected, for even the son of man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many.

33:57.474 --> 34:03.942
We're told that in his kingdom, the first shall be last and the last shall be first, that the poor in spirit, theirs is the kingdom of heaven.

34:04.342 --> 34:08.528
That those persecuted for righteousness sake, theirs is the kingdom.

34:08.548 --> 34:13.694
In coming underneath his rule and his reign requires something completely unexpected.

34:14.455 --> 34:19.441
Unless one is born again, he cannot see the kingdom of God.

34:20.302 --> 34:22.345
Because he didn't come to conquer the nations.

34:22.925 --> 34:25.148
He came to conquer a greater foe.

34:25.689 --> 34:26.770
In fact, we're told

34:26.978 --> 34:36.890
before he's born, that his mother will bear a son, and you shall call his name Jesus, for he will save his people from their sins.

34:37.671 --> 34:45.240
And the most important thing that you can do is to ask, how can I come underneath the rule and reign of this king and be part of his kingdom?

34:46.001 --> 34:49.805
Seek ye first the kingdom of God in his righteousness.

34:50.727 --> 34:53.650
Now luckily for us, we see that king in full,

34:53.890 --> 34:55.775
because we see Him in the rear view mirror.

34:55.795 --> 34:59.886
That is our Lord, our Savior, our King of Kings, Jesus Christ.

35:00.307 --> 35:04.178
And He will return in the book of Revelation as a King.

35:04.706 --> 35:13.781
written on his thigh will be the name king of kings and lord of lords and his revelation tells us he will sit on a throne and he will rule and reign as he was intended.

35:14.061 --> 35:17.887
And the entire story of the Bible ultimately is pointing to him.

35:17.928 --> 35:25.540
All of these kings are showing us that need of a different type of king ruling and reigning under a different type of kingdom.

35:25.620 --> 35:31.730
And that desire is natural and good, but we need something so very different.

35:32.034 --> 35:37.320
because you and I are so much, very much the same as Israel back in their day.

35:37.380 --> 35:38.962
We're really not that different, are we?

35:39.723 --> 35:43.147
If you think about it, God rules and reigns in our life as well.

35:43.508 --> 35:46.151
He is our sovereign king, at least he desires to be.

35:46.851 --> 35:50.276
And God's heart is that his people would be distinct that they would live different.

35:50.696 --> 35:55.742
He's called us as the church to look and to act and to believe different than the world around us.

35:56.383 --> 35:59.186
King Jesus says we should be salt and light

35:59.490 --> 36:04.895
And yet like Israel, we struggle with that idea of living distinct and not blending in.

36:04.915 --> 36:11.762
We too have a tendency to settle for less than God's best, to replace God with lesser kings.

36:12.283 --> 36:16.267
We have these little functional saviors or kings that we think will solve our problems.

36:16.767 --> 36:27.218
We have a fundamental misunderstanding of what's best for us, and we simply think, God, if you will acquiesce to my desires and my needs, because I know better than you, my life will be better.

36:27.394 --> 36:29.777
And sometimes God does just that.

36:30.477 --> 36:34.482
And He gives us exactly what we ask for.

36:35.243 --> 36:40.028
He gives us little saws in our life and says, okay, how'd that go for you?

36:40.648 --> 36:42.290
I gave you what you wanted.

36:42.871 --> 36:44.132
Is that still what you wanted?

36:44.573 --> 36:46.034
How did that go for you?

36:46.535 --> 36:51.861
To help us understand, maybe we're not the end-all, be-all sovereign king of our own lives.

36:52.181 --> 36:55.044
Maybe we really don't know exactly what we need.

36:55.505 --> 36:56.786
And maybe he does.

36:57.282 --> 37:05.066
And the whole purpose of this series, the whole purpose of the Bible is to remind us of that fact, that God rules and reigns in our life.

37:05.507 --> 37:11.666
And the greatest question that we can ask and answer is how do I come underneath the rule and reign of King Jesus?

37:11.970 --> 37:17.756
Many of us in the room have done that, and we're learning how to operate underneath his kingdom with the new set of rules and new ideas.

37:18.196 --> 37:23.122
Many of us here haven't, and that's a wonderful thing that you're here in exploring that with us.

37:23.142 --> 37:29.949
But as we journey through this series, every week we want to remind our eyes and our hearts and our heads that is the end goal.

37:30.509 --> 37:34.533
All of these kings were there to show Israel something so much more important.

37:34.553 --> 37:38.898
And in the same way for us looking in the rear view mirror, it is ultimately about him.

37:39.266 --> 37:41.890
the king of kings and how we come underneath his reign.

37:42.371 --> 37:50.062
So as we go on this journey together, I invite you to see Jesus differently through the eyes of these kings and the idea of what God wants to call us to.

37:50.483 --> 37:58.194
To be those who will live in his reign under his rule and be servants of his kingdom, Jesus Christ, our Lord and Savior.

37:58.215 --> 37:58.615
Let's pray.

37:59.597 --> 38:03.623
Father, we thank you for your rule and reign in our life.

38:03.643 --> 38:08.530
And we thank you for Christ who we get to see clearly because of what he has done on our behalf.

38:08.802 --> 38:20.358
And as you show us Him as a reigning king in our lives, Father, I pray that our hearts would magnify who He is, that we would be blown away by what we're to see in these earthly kings.

38:20.478 --> 38:25.284
Some of them very good, pictures of who Christ ultimately is called to be in our lives.

38:25.745 --> 38:27.868
And would we submit to that rule and reign in His life?

38:28.409 --> 38:30.712
And Father, I pray for any here that maybe they're not there yet.

38:30.892 --> 38:38.322
They haven't understand both the lamb and the lion who came the first time to lay His life down for us, who rules so differently.

38:38.562 --> 38:41.832
than any other king is he came to die for those whom he loved.

38:42.153 --> 38:46.827
Father, I pray in this journey that they would seek Christ rightly in who he is to us.

38:47.248 --> 38:48.632
Father, we love you and we thank you.

38:48.652 --> 38:49.675
In Jesus' name we pray.

38:50.217 --> 38:50.578
Amen.

